sudo systemctl restart dnsmasq

Key details:

DHCP only on eth0
DNS disabled with port=0
No default gateway advertised
No DNS server advertised
FreeSWITCH service dependency on Ethernet/DHCP/relay init

FreeSWITCH waits for the isolated Ethernet address before starting.

Helper:

sudo tee /usr/local/bin/bella-wait-eth0 >/dev/null <<'EOF'
#!/usr/bin/env bash
set -euo pipefail

IFACE="${1:-eth0}"
IP="${2:-192.168.50.1}"
TIMEOUT="${3:-30}"

for i in $(seq 1 "$TIMEOUT"); do
  if ip -4 addr show dev "$IFACE" | grep -q "${IP}/"; then
    exit 0
  fi
  sleep 1
done

echo "ERROR: ${IFACE} did not get ${IP} within ${TIMEOUT}s" >&2
ip -br addr >&2
exit 1
EOF

sudo chmod 755 /usr/local/bin/bella-wait-eth0

Service uses:

ExecStartPre=/usr/local/bin/bella-wait-eth0 eth0 192.168.50.1 30
FreeSWITCH systemd service settings

Important service settings we used:

User=freeswitch
Group=freeswitch
WorkingDirectory=/usr/local/freeswitch

ExecStart=/usr/local/freeswitch/bin/freeswitch -ncwait -nonat
ExecReload=/usr/local/freeswitch/bin/fs_cli -x "reloadxml"
ExecStop=/usr/local/freeswitch/bin/fs_cli -x "shutdown elegant"

LimitNOFILE=500000
LimitNPROC=20000
LimitRTPRIO=89
LimitRTTIME=infinity
Nice=-10

NoNewPrivileges=no
PrivateTmp=yes

Critical note: NoNewPrivileges=no was required because FreeSWITCH runs sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay from bgsystem. With NoNewPrivileges=yes, the relay command did not work.

sudoers rule for relay control

FreeSWITCH and the setup user need passwordless access only to the relay script.

sudo tee /etc/sudoers.d/disco-relay >/dev/null <<'EOF'
bella ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/disco-relay
freeswitch ALL=(root) NOPASSWD: /usr/local/bin/disco-relay
EOF

sudo chmod 440 /etc/sudoers.d/disco-relay
sudo visudo -c
Boot-time relay/actuator initialization

We added a oneshot service to force the actuator into a known lowered/off state before FreeSWITCH starts.

Defaults file:

sudo tee /etc/default/disco-relay-boot >/dev/null <<'EOF'
DISCO_RELAY_BOOT_COMMAND="initialize 10 0"
EOF

Service:

[Unit]
Description=Initialize Disco Actuator on Boot
After=local-fs.target
Before=freeswitch.service
Wants=freeswitch.service

[Service]
Type=oneshot
EnvironmentFile=/etc/default/disco-relay-boot
ExecStart=/bin/bash -c '/usr/local/bin/disco-relay ${DISCO_RELAY_BOOT_COMMAND}'
TimeoutStartSec=90
RemainAfterExit=yes

[Install]
WantedBy=multi-user.target

Enable:

sudo systemctl daemon-reload
sudo systemctl enable disco-relay-boot.service
File ownership fixes

We repeatedly made sure FreeSWITCH owned its config and sounds:

sudo chown -R freeswitch:freeswitch /usr/local/freeswitch/conf
sudo chown -R freeswitch:freeswitch /usr/local/freeswitch/sounds

For the custom recorded greeting directory:

sudo mkdir -p /usr/local/freeswitch/sounds/en/us/callie/disco
sudo chown -R freeswitch:freeswitch /usr/local/freeswitch/sounds/en/us/callie/disco
Raspberry Pi GPIO access model

The relay script runs as root through sudo, rather than trying to grant FreeSWITCH direct GPIO access. This avoided permission issues around GPIO/pinctrl and /run/disco-relay.lock.

Manual use:

sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay status
sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay brake
sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay raise 10 40
sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay lower 10 60

Optional convenience alias for the bella user:

echo "alias disco-relay='sudo /usr/local/bin/disco-relay'" >> ~/.bashrc
source ~/.bashrc
